AGI - The wreck of a Luftwaffe plane carrying troops and means to North Africa for the Afrika Korps of Feldmaresciallo Erwin Rommel was located on the seabed off Bastia, Corsica. The discovery was made possible by the use of the Rov, the underwater inspection tool piloted remotely, by the Italian-Swiss engineer Guido Gay, known for bringing to light numerous relics deep abyssal, including that of Corazzato Roma. At 500 metres deep, the remains of a Messerschmitt Me 323 Gigant were found, built in only 200 units, a gigantic transport aircraft that Luftwaffe engaged during the Second World War to send troops and supplies to Africa. The activity of the Me 323 had long been identified by the allied counter-spionage thanks to the 'Ultra' decryptions.
This has allowed many downfalls from the Anglo-American aviation, which took place in several theatres of the Mediterranean Sea, with heavy hunting Bristol Beaufighter. Even the plane discovered by Guido Gay was shot down in one of these interception actions. &nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The marine researcher and expert in historical documentation Massimo Bertoni also discovered an important document of the first Gruppenfhurer Storm of Luftwaffe, dated 12 October 1943, in which precise reference is made of the action that led to the removal of the plane. The German report mentions the take-off of two Me 323 loaded with military vehicles on the evening of 30 September of that year from Bastia airport. After a few minutes, about 12 nautical miles from the coast of the French island, the two "Gigants" were targeted by allied aircraft who concentrated their fire especially on one of the two Me 323, the one shot down, while the other managed rather unconscious to return to the base of departure.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Equipped with six radial engines, a wingspan of 55 meters and a length of almost 29 meters, the Gigant Me 323 had an operating autonomy of about 1300 km and was able to carry up to 120 men or an equivalent load including heavy vehicles up to 12 tons. The maximum speed from the plane was 250 km/h. He was armed with 7 13 mm MG machine guns and two anti-aircraft guns. Guido Gay engineer graduated from Politecnico di Milano in 1964, of Piedmontese origin, Italian and Swiss nationality, is particularly known as "inventor" designer and manufacturer in various fields of technology. Passionate sailor and sailor, in the early 1970s he began studying teleguided submarine vehicles in history as a pioneer of this technique.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

